<p><b>Arthur Machen</b> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/ˈmækən/</a></span>) (March 3, 1863 – December 15, 1947) was a leading <a href="/wiki/Wales" title="Wales">Welsh</a> <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a> of the 1890s. He is best known for his influential <a href="/wiki/Supernatural_fiction" title="Supernatural fiction">supernatural</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fantasy_fiction" title="Fantasy fiction" class="mw-redirect">fantasy</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Horror_fiction" title="Horror fiction">horror fiction</a>. He also is well known for his leading role in creating the <a href="/wiki/Legend" title="Legend">legend</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Angels_of_Mons" title="Angels of Mons">Angels of Mons</a>.</p>
